questionTemplates.text:
M: How do you like your tea, with milk or sugar?
W: Not too much milk and no sugar, please.
{a}

M: How much will it cost to send this letter to Beijing?
W: It weights half an ounce. That'll be six dollars by airmail.
{a}

W: I am worried about Jenny going to college. College students are so wild nowadays.
M: Actually, only a few are like that. Most students are too busy studying to have time to cause trouble.
{a}

M: Now, what's your problem, Madam?
W: Oh, yes. My husband bought this yellow skirt here yesterday. It is very nice, but it's not the colour I want. Have you got any blue ones?
{a}

M: Shall I come and take you to the railway station?
W: No, thanks, I'll manage. It's not far any way.
{a}

M: What do you think of people suing McDonalds for making them fat?
W: Well. Its food doesn't make you fat. But eating too much of it does! How about chocolate and ice cream? Are they all responsible? It's silly!
{a}

M: Can I help you?
W: Yes. I'm looking for a blue raincoat, Size 36.
{a}

W: Do you like Mr. Zhang's classes?
M: I never miss his class. you know.
{a}

W: Did you see the car that girl just drove past in?
M: That wasn't a bad-looking car. I wouldn't mind having one like it.
{a}

M: I need your ID and ac count number before I can cash your check.
W: Sure, here's my passport and driving license and my account number is on this card.
{a}

W: Excuse me. I'd like to buy a desk for my little son. I don't have any particular brand in mind, but it should be less than 50 dollars.
M: OK. We have a large selection of small desks for young children.
{a}

W: Hello, Joe, Haven't seen you for quite a while. Are you fine?
M: Oh, yes, but not a thing to go against me. I had a car accident, only some minor injuries though.
{a}

W: I hear your boss has a real good impression of you and he is thinking about giving you two more days off each month.
M: I hope not. I'd rather get more work hours so I can get enough bucks to help out my two kids at college.
{a}

F: Which sweater do you like better, the cotton one or the woolen one?
M: I like the red woolen one.
{a}

F: The film is very interesting.
M: I don't think so.
{a}

M: Waitress! This meat is like stone! It's enough to break every tooth in your mouth.
F: Perhaps you'd like to change your order, sir.
{a}

M: I want to change my ticket for the plane at 6:00 tomorrow morning.
W: Sorry, sir. The ticket for this flight is now unavailable.
{a}

W: The shirt is fifty dollars, but I only have fifteen.
M: I can lend you the rest, Kate.
{a}

M: I can't find my new tie. I need it for tonight's party.
W: Let's look for it later. Right now I need your help fixing this shelf before I paint it.
{a}

M: Your apartment always looks so good, so spotless and mine is such a mess.
W: I've been at the lab all the week. It is my roommate's doing.
{a}

W: They may be proud of their new facilities, but frankly I'm disappointed. The nurses are not friendly and everything seems to be running behind schedule.
M: Not to mention the fact that it's noisy because no one Observes visiting hours.
{a}

W: How long can I keep those books?
M: At most one month. After one month, you must come to renew them, or else you will be fined.
{a}

W: I feel so lonely sitting at home by myself every day.
M: Hmm, that's quite a problem. Might it be an idea to try to have a trip?
{a}

W: can you give a hand, Mike? I want tomove a few heavy items to the car.
M: I'd like to but I am already five minutes late for my appointment with Mr. Jason, and the office is on the other side of the campus.
{a}
